items.name: Kate Bush (1978-82 era - CHECKPOINT)
items.description:
THERE IS A LORA VERSION OF THIS MODEL AVAILABLE. IT IS EXACTLY THE SAME MODEL AS THIS ONE, EXCEPT IN A DIFFERENT AND LIGHTER FORMAT.

Shivam Dreambooth of British singer/songwriter Kate Bush, using 165 ref images and 1980 (real) reg images, for 20,000 steps. The period covered is around 1978-82.

This is a tricky model to use, and among the least 'one-click' of my models. In general, keep the sampling steps no higher than about 60, ideally on the good Karras interpreters, and keep working the picture until it assembles. You can move the steps up as you go in for detail later.

I generally use these models in complex workflows, inpainting faces after initial T2Is, and using ControlNet extensively. So if you're hoping for one-click prompt magic, my models aren't data-curated with this in mind, but rather as tools for traditional workflows that use Photoshop and other older methods.

This model may produce subject-accurate NSFW output unless countered in negative prompts.

items.name: Colossus (Deadpool CGI version)
items.description:
More support needed ! Out of colab credits, I'm gonna run out of models to post. You can support me here to be able to render better models (https://ko-fi.com/djo226). Supporters can request model.

You can also subscribe to my Patreon and get exclusive models.

Colossus (Piotr "Peter" Nikolayevich Rasputin) is a character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. Created by writer Len Wein and artist Dave Cockrum, he first appeared in Giant-Size X-Men #1 (May 1975).

A Russian mutant, he is a member of the X-Men. Colossus is able to transform himself into metallic form, making him the physically strongest of the team. He is portrayed as quiet, honest, and virtuous. He has had a fairly consistent presence in X-Men-related comic books since his debut. A talented artist, he only reluctantly agrees to use his powers in combat, feeling it is his responsibility to use his abilities for the betterment of human- and mutant-kind.

In film, Donald MacKinnon made a cameo appearance as Colossus in X-Men before Daniel Cudmore took over for X2, X-Men: The Last Stand, and X-Men: Days of Future Past while Stefan KapiÄiÄ‡ voices a separate iteration of Colossus in Deadpool, Deadpool 2 and the Marvel Cinematic Universe film Deadpool 3.

Prompt : Colossus, realistic, natural lighting, post-processing, ultra realistic, highly detailed, very detailed, cinematic, hyper realistic, intricate scenery, sharp, photo by Annie Leibovitz, film, studio lighting, ultra realistic, bokeh, sharp features <lora:Colossus:0.7>

Negative prompt: (deformed iris, deformed pupils, semi-realistic, cgi, 3d, render, sketch, cartoon, drawing, anime, mutated hands and fingers:1.4), (deformed, distorted, disfigured:1.3), poorly drawn, bad anatomy, wrong anatomy, extra limb, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected limbs, mutation, mutated, ugly, disgusting, amputation

Steps: 50, Sampler: DDIM, CFG scale: 12, Seed: -1, Face restoration: GFPGAN, Size: 768x1024, Model hash: 81086e2b3f, Model: realisticVisionV20_v20

Face restoration is optional, may provide better result if not activated.

Use Colossus as trigger. You might have to lower the Lora's weight to 0.3 sometimes depending of the action asked.

items.name: Image Dataset Manager
items.description:
Image Dataset Manager

Hello, guys!

Let me introduce the Image Dataset Manager.

This tool is great for organizing images and creating annotations for them. It can be invaluable in various fields where you need to work with a large number of images, from game development to scientific research. In our case, we will use it for creating datasets.

Instruction:Â 

After installing the fast setup, we open IDM and click on "Create Dataset."

Now, we give a name to our future dataset and link folders with images. Then, we go to the "Images" tab.

Here, we encounter three columns:

1 - All our images from all folders together. You can select images one by one or multiple using Shift. Ctrl + A selects all images. There's also a possibility to filter images by tags at the top.

2 - Information about the selected image. Full description and a field for a unique description {custom} for each image. There's also an "Export" checkbox that determines whether the image will be exported or not.

3 - A window with tags and the main dataset description formula.

Now, let's take a closer look at the third column since it's our main field for work. Click on "+" and create our first group of tags.

Group Name - The name of the group, which we will use to create the description formula.Â 

Prefix - Text that will be added to the group at the beginning. For example, "With a" or just a space.

Suffix - Text that will be added at the end, e.g., a comma.

Join String - Text used to join 2 or more tags from the same group. By default, it's just a space.

Tag List - Enter our tags here.

Description Template String - Here, we enter the formula based on which the description will be constructed. We use {Group Name}, for example:

Using the formula and tag groups provides almost limitless possibilities for descriptions!

Once the dataset description is ready, it's time to proceed to export.

Center crop/Resize - Allows manipulation of image sizes.

Flatten alpha - Fills the alpha channel with the chosen color.

Export Path - The path where the dataset will be saved. There's an option to save all images separately by groups. For this, use the formula {30/Class}_{Class}.

{30/Class} - Calculates the number of required repetitions for 1 epoch based on the number of images. In my tests, I found that the number 30 works well for medium datasets targeting 7-8 epochs.

{Class} - Adds the necessary tag group name to the filename.

As a result, I obtained the following dataset:

Done!Â 

As you can see, this tool is very simple to use and yet powerful when it comes to annotating a large number of images.Â 

The tool is still in its early version and actively being developed. If you want to participate in the development or report a bug, you can refer to the appropriate branches on the project's GitHub.

My Patreon where I post guides and models

Thank you for your attention!

items.name: Polygonal drawing style
items.description:
Only for SD 2.1

Polygonal drawing style, often referred to as low poly art, is a modern artistic movement characterized by the simplification of an image into geometric shapes, specifically polygons. It's a technique widely used in 3D modeling, especially in the field of video games and animations, but it's also popular in 2D graphic design and illustration.

In a polygonal drawing, the subject is broken down and recreated using only polygonal facets. The number of polygons can vary: using fewer polygons results in a more abstract, faceted appearance, while using more polygons can result in a more detailed and realistic image.

Color choice plays a significant role in this style, with each polygon typically filled with a solid color. Shading and lighting effects are often achieved through the use of gradients or varying the color between polygons.

Overall, the polygonal drawing style is a unique blend of modern digital techniques and fundamental artistic principles. It's a versatile style that can range from highly abstract to near photorealistic, offering endless possibilities for creativity.

items.name: amiya arknights (old)
items.description:
This model is uploaded just for a test. A better LoRA of amiya is here: https://civitai.com/models/121403/amiya-arknights

All pts can be found on https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1eFmfDmp2yalPXj0K1gEQBCMGvusqW9eP?usp=sharing

This is the README on the abovementioned link:

User Guide for This Embedding

The current path contains the following:
1. 'README.txt', this document, a guide for usage.
2. 'embedding' folder, containing the intermediate embedding file of each step in the training process (named 'amiya-yyy.pt', where 'amiya' is the role name, yyy is the number of training steps, such as 13250, and the full name after combination is 'amiya-13250.pt')
3. 'xxx.png/xxx_meta.txt', is the test images of this embedding, and the detailed prompt and model configuration used. 'xxx.png' contains a table composed of pictures. The integer number on the top represents the number of steps, while the float number on the left represents the weight used in prompt. The table reflects the actual performance of embedding in various states.

Usage:
1. When using, copy the 'amiya-*.pt' files under the 'embedding' folder to the './embeddings' sub folder of your webui working path.
2. Check 'xxx.png' to find out the best state range of embedding. Specifically, please pay attention to whether the following conditions appear in the image:
  a) Bad background, and the characters are distorted or pixelated (too high weight)
  b) Whether the character's appearance features are seriously lost (too low weight, or too low steps)
  c) For the pictures of bikini and nude, whether the characters still wear the original clothes instead of swimwear/stripping (the number of steps is too high, or the characters are coupled with his/her clothes)
3. Based on the basic configuration of 'xxx_meta.txt', use the X/Y Plot function to further tune the steps and weights
4. Configure your own prompt, draw your image.

[!!!IMPORTANT!!!] Instructions:
1. This embedding is trained with a self-modified version of stable-diffusion-webui, which uses program script to automatically grab the images of xxx from the Internet, and conducts training after image-recognition-based data cleaning and tagging. The developer of the program script is narugo@126.com. There is no human involved in the whole training process. Therefore, the quality of this embedding will largely depend on the quantity and quality of data on the Internet.
2. Our 'xxx.png'/'xxx_meta.txt' is only a simple test and cannot fully represent the real quality of embedding. The quality of the final output image depends on further prompt and settings.
3. In 'xxx.png', the used keywords of character features are automatically recognized based on images from the Internet. Therefore, there may be some errors and omissions, which may lead to deviations in the characters in 'xxx.png' (e.g. hair color, long/short hair, chest circumference, clothes style, etc.). these problems can be easily fixed by adding or deleting certain keywords.
4. For the current character 'amiya', the feature keywords detected by the program script specifically include: [brown hair, rabbit ears, animal ears, long hair, blue eyes, jacket, jewelry, black jacket, hair between eyes]

LyCORIS weights should be between 0.9-1.2
